==English==
===Etymology===
{{etystub}}

Supposedly coined by Simpsons writer George Meyer. First appears in episode 9F14, "Duffless".

Earlier origins from [[w:Scooby Doo]] cartoons of the 1970s.

===Transitive verb===
{{en-infl-reg-consonant|yoink||}}

#{{slang}} To [[steal]]. To [[take]].
#:''I'm going to '''yoink''' the last piece of toast if it nobody else lays claim to it.''

===Interjection===
'''yoink!'''

#{{slang}} Used to accompany an act of yoinking.
<!--
# An [[exclamation]] that, when uttered in conjunction with taking an object, signifies that you are [[steal]]ing said object.  Used [[ironically]] by the [[thief]], as it draws attention to what would normally be a [[clandestine]] act.
#: ''Usage Note'' Should be said with a rising tone, in imitation of the character, Homer Simpson, who first used it.
-->

